    EDMA form difference matrix

    Peter Solymos

    edma04-form-difference.Rmd

    Form difference (FDM) is calculated as the ratio of form matrices (FM) from the numerator and denominator objects following Lele and Richtsmeier (1992, 1995): FDM(A,B) = FM(B)/FM(A). Form matrices are formed as pairwise Euclidean distances between landmarks from EDMA fit objects using the estimated mean forms.

    Bootstrap distribution is based on fixing the reference FM and taking the ration between the reference FM and the bootstrap FMs from the other object. The ref_denom argument can be used to control which object is the reference:

    library(EDMAinR)
#> EDMAinR 0.1-3     2020-06-12

file1 <- system.file("extdata/crouzon/Crouzon_P0_Global_MUT.xyz",
    package="EDMAinR")
x1 <- read_xyz(file1)

file2 <- system.file("extdata/crouzon/Crouzon_P0_Global_NON-MUT.xyz",
    package="EDMAinR")
x2 <- read_xyz(file2)

numerator <- edma_fit(x1)
denominator <- edma_fit(x2)

fdm <- edma_fdm(numerator, denominator, B=25)
fdm
#> EDMA form difference matrix
#> Call: edma_fdm(numerator = numerator, denominator = denominator, B = 25)
#> 25 bootstrap runs (ref: denominator)
#> T=1.598, p=0

    Here is how to do the global T-test: the T-statistic is based on the pairwise distanced in the FM, taking the max/min.

    T_test(fdm)
#> 
#>  Bootstrap based EDMA T-test
#> 
#> data:  form difference matrix
#> T-value = 1.598, B = 25, p-value < 2.2e-16
plot_Ttest(fdm)

    The local CI base test is done via the stacked FDM and the confidence intervals (landmark labels get really busy):

    Influential landmarks are identified by leaving one landmark out, then comparing the T-statistic with the value based on all the landmarks. The existing bootstrap distribution of the mean form is used (i.e.Â no re-estimation of the mean form):

    head(infl <- get_influence(fdm))
#>   landmark    Tdrop    lower    upper
#> 1    amsph 1.597980 1.078682 1.420971
#> 2      bas 1.597980 1.078682 1.420971
#> 3     cpsh 1.597980 1.078682 1.420971
#> 4    ethma 1.311473 1.071003 1.312708
#> 5    ethmp 1.311473 1.071003 1.312708
#> 6    laalf 1.597980 1.078682 1.420971
plot(infl)

    The ordination and cluster dendrogram shows the two sets of specimens from the 2 objects:

    plot_ord(fdm)

    plot_clust(fdm)

    The 2D and 3D plots produces a plot of the mean form from the reference object (â€˜prototypeâ€™). Influential landmarks are colored red. Lines represent distances between landmarks, <1 differences are colored blue, >1 differences are colored red.
